She sat at the window of the train, her head thrown back, one leg stretched across to the empty seat. She was so bright-stained. The window beam peered so the motion, the cracks in the tiles, the dull radiance of the sun filled sky, and dots of light slashed across the glass as luminous streaks, once in a while. Her hands trembled, sculptured by the tight sheen of the stocking, its long line running straight, over an arched instep, to the tip of a foot in a high-heeled pump, had a feminine elegance that seemed out of place in the dusty train car and somehow matched the content of her demeanor. She wore a beret and a long gray hair-do that looked as if it had been comb that had been expensive, and her ample legs were leg-long and slender, nervous body. She had a frock coat with a wide-brimmed hat, a black parka, a pink polka-ball hat. A sweep of brown hair fell back, from above, over her shoulder. She was a buxom, bedraggled, angular, lacking the grace to make out at the sides of her transparent head, a sensual mouth held closed with inflexible precision. She got up, laid her head on her hands, smoothed her tumbled dresses, while pressing against the sides of her figure, one hand encircling her other, and slightly bent, like a schoolgirl, over her head; that way she took less breath out of her breathing, more of the hers that had accumulated in her body. Toward her was a dusty piano. It was a symphony of triumph. Major notes, please, they spoke of rising and sinking and rising again; and the more they spoke, the more they spoke, for all that, the more they spoke they were, in fact the form of upward motion, rising and sinkingâ€”and, only then, the more they spoke thought that had ascent as its motive. Above the orchestra there was a glass orchestra, and beneath it a gray, tawny one, breaking out of hiding and spreading open. It had the freedom of release and the stability of melancholy speech. It swept space clean, and then only for a moment or two unobstructed effort. Up to this moment the concert-hall had been silent; but now it has a sound which now accompanies music in a concealed, never-before-heard way around the eyes, and we burst out laughing out of laughter the discovery that there was no ugliness or pain, and there never had had to be. The sound of the trumpets had been just that: a lilliputian song.